Not at all. What I’m saying is that this kind of work constitutes an attempt to quantify moral values, which relates to the question posed by the article heading you referred to: is this a good thing? I think this is an unanswerable question, because any answer you could give is predicated on one sort of doctrine or another — and like I alluded to earlier, organisms deal in practices, not theories supported by doctrines. So if life poses you with an unanswerable question, it might be best not to answer, rather than enter into a type of Pascalian bargain. If what’s “good” is founded in metaphysics, which is technically neither true or false (no doctrines here), then our understanding of math (in this case, statistical tracking) and language comes down to symbolic practices. The dangerous trap I was referring earlier is what often happens with statistical analysis: it feels the need to explain rather than to describe. When there’s too much emphasis on the former, we find ourselves trying to explain rather than describe. We shouldn’t be trying to explain why something is either good or bad, we should be trying to describe it. Description is what precedes understanding, not explanation. This is one of the false problems of language I talked about earlier. If meaning exists, it can’t be said — only shown. Therefore, an attempt to apply a good/bad judgment to something that tries to quantify morality is misguided because all it’s doing is displacing the problem: It might be good today, it might be bad tomorrow. It might be good for my business, it might be bad for yours. These are all false problems, and they all stem from the dilemmas posed to us by realist interpretations and structures of the world. I think you’re misunderstanding the setup. The top graph is the showing the model trained on the normal MNIST, while the second one is training on MNIST with random labels. There is no “white noise”, which would be permuting or randomizing some of the x variables, but the labels are fully random. So the data being trained on is basically contradictory (a “3” is labelled as a 4,5,1, ect). Thats why the held out set gets 10% accuracy. Whats important is the training set accuracy, which tells us if the model has issue when the data is basically meaningless. It’s impossible to do any better (or worse) than 10% on unseen data with random labels. They point this out in the paper : “The test error, of course, is no better than random chance as there is no correlation between the training labels and the test labels”.

Analysis of variance (AONVA) a way of testing hypothesis when there are more than two means involved. T-test is used only for two means comparison and its repeatedly using may cause a severe inflation of Type I error. Fisher developed the ANOVA and that’s why ANOVA use F value in report. In hypothesis analysis, the null hypothesis is usually set as insignificant differences among several conditions (variables) and alternative hypothesis is usually set as significant differences among these conditions. Since variances can be categorized as random factors and known factor effects, when known factors has a much higher possibility than that of random effects, we can take it as the effect of existing variables (significnance). As for types, there are one-way ANOVA, two-way ANOVA, factorial ANOVA, repeated measure ANOVA, ANCOVA, and MANOVA to deal with different situations.

Nice. FUD, fear, uncertainty, and doubt as a marketing device has been around for quite a while now, and is currently being applied to AI by some, unfortunately. The implementation of AI is, and will continue to be, driven by value, within a consumer driven market, as has and will continue to be the case. That said, the emergence of AI will be both shocking to some domains, while at the same time, to overall society, very, very subtle. We are already there — see how subtle. Next, AI exists within a constraint context. Historically, AI constraints have been both technical as well as commercial. In the 80’s technical limitations started to be addressed, then in the 90’s with, believe it or not, check signing, commercial demand began to drive subtle advances in AI. Looking forward, the commercial demand for AI will continue to be driven by a combination of improving service delivery and analysis of a plethora of data, whether that data exists as real-time streaming, as in self-driving cars and online consumerism, or retrospective analysis, for example the result of IoT activity. Within the forward facing context, the rate of adoption and refinement of AI will exist on and within the adoption of other technologies, for example Blockchain. As the current HUGE investments in Blockchain drives business value, and as a result, becomes more pervasive across our activities, and as compute resources continue to increase in power and decrease in cost, the ability to implement AI across a more standard stack that cuts across almost all of us — that is, a Blockchain representation of an individual entity, the ability to cost-effectively implement AI to subtly provide wide ranging services will be implemented — a result of cost-effective business value. Blockchain, in this context, is an AI enabler example, just one of many.

Deep learning is definitely the way of the future but it still has some hurdles to overcome. Compared to more traditional methods like Random Forests or Linear Models, there are a LOT of knobs that you need to turn. How many neurons do you need? How many layers should there be? These are just a few of the questions that you need to answer before you can even start building the model. While there are rules of thumb you can use, there are an infinite number of architectures you can create which only amplifies the difficulty. Once someone overcomes these hurdles and creates an easy to use framework, I bet neural networks will be expanded to even more applications that what they are being used for today.

Why is your organization building a connected system? Whatever particular story fits your business, industrial investment in IoT is about value creation. It’s about collecting data from environments and assets, and transforming raw machine signals and external events into information used to improve performance. Greater reliability. Faster time to market. Reduced costs. Better customer relationships. Increased revenue. These outcomes are made possible when you know the state of your machines and the world around you at each moment in time. These are the outputs of the new Systems of Intelligence created by data-focused, flexible, secure, and scalable IoT solutions.

Many, if not most, people don’t mind seeing recommendations on new books to read or movies to see, based on their own prior selections and what other similar buyers buy. I really like the way you laid out this article and the one about statistics. I think one reason we don’t see a lot of statistics used anymore is that as we have more data, we have less uncertainty. Before we had tools to collect web analytics, for example, we might do a survey of our customers via phone or email and get about 5–10% response rate. This requires statistics to extrapolate the other 90–95% who didn’t give us any response. Now, we can use in-app analytics to measure every customer’s interaction from start to finish, resulting in us having ~99–100% of the data.

Thanks for the great breakdown. I would put Javascript in the top list along with R and Python. This is because Javascript is the language of the internet and the true touchpoint to any models we create. Data Scientists are meant to make data-driven products, not run analysis in a vacuum. Data scientists capable of whipping together quick prototypes using Javascript have an immense advantage over those focused solely on preparing data and training models. Javascript allows our analyses to benefit from user feedback; something as important as any statistical validation. Stakeholders get little value from a slideshow of charts. Javascript turns machine learning into real-world, working applications, and it doesn’t take long to build a simple html/css/js application people can interact with. Of course D3.js extends these benefits even further. I encourage data scientists to know a language that allows them to assemble real applications people can use, and there is no better language than Javascript for this purpose.

When it comes to data erasure, it would seem many people think that clicking “empty trash” is adequate. That’s unfortunate, because not only is that thinking inadequate in most typical cases, it’s also extremely dangerous. What we typically consider an act of “data erasing” in the modern workspace is often fundamentally insecure and dangerous, and relying upon these methods can expose you, your clients, and your work to monumental threats.

While this is an interesting approach there are several factors that are not given what I would deem sufficient weight. First and foremost being adaptability to differing military challenges. Napoleon effectively fought but one type of system as did most of those mentioned, furthermore his most successful campaigns were generally fought in some of the most developed parts of Europe. Alexander the Great fought a wide array of opponents (heavy infantry, archery, elephants, steppe cavalry, siege) and demonstrated an ability to defeat them all. Strategic mandates and the responsibility for recognizing responsibility for such decisions are quite important. Once again Alexander excels, note how he eradicated the Persian fleet or maintained the logistics of his infantry biased army across a considerable and diverse terrain for a singularly long period of continuous campaigning nearly unrivaled by any of his peers. Lastly it is worth paying more attention to the entirety of one’s career and recognizing the limitations of source material. Tamerlane for instance obviously won numerous battles against great odds over a vast expanse in an inordinately long career yet he does not even get a mention.
